<DOCNO> AP900810-0003 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
anger and frustration still simmer in watts 
25 years after a week of rioting reduced entire blocks to charred 
ruins and seared black rage onto the american conscience 
but watts today is not the powder keg it was when the streets of 
los angeles exploded on aug 11 1965 and burned for six nights 
and days according to residents community activists and academics 
some people say such postriot developments as a new shopping 
center and a health clinic have improved the community others 
contend that negative forces are responsible for keeping the lid on 
any more riots 
in recent years gangs and drugs have joined the longtime 
problems of crime joblessness and despair making the area both 
violent and stagnant watts today directs its rage at itself 
rather than at society reducing the risk of another riot but doing 
nothing to solve the communitys woes 
drugs are a deterrent a lazy deterrent said ted watkins 
jr president of watts labor community action committee a leader 
in the effort to rebuild the area i dont think that in 1990 the 
will is here for another riot 
watts became a symbol of innercity anger sparked by an event 
that didnt even happen inside the community of 30500 people eight 
miles due south of downtown los angeles 
four blocks west of watts two white california highway patrol 
officers stopped a 21yearold black motorist for investigation of 
erratic driving 
a scuffle started between the patrolmen and the motorist a 
crowd gathered and quickly grew angry rocks were thrown more 
police arrived the crowd swelled 
in about an hour the disturbance spread to surrounding 
communities including watts rioters torched buildings looted 
stores and pulled white drivers from their cars and beat them 
snipers took to the rooftops 
a 50squaremile area became a combat zone national guard jeeps 
with machine guns patrolled the streets 
when it was all over 34 people were dead 4000 others 
arrested and damage was estimated at 40 million a stretch of 
103rd street was lined by burntout skeletons of buildings giving 
it the name charcoal alley 
the mccone commission named after chairman john a mccone 
former head of the cia issued a 101page report finding that the 
cycle of poverty and despair gripping the area set the stage for 
the riot 
the report recommended a series of ambitious reforms from job 
training to efficient public transportation 
many community activists and politicians say some important 
reforms went into place and made watts a better community 
charcoal alley has become a pleasant street with a post office 
city council field office shopping center with a bank and 
supermarket and a station on the citys new blue line light rail 
system 
relations with the police department are the best ever many 
say thanks in part to increased minority recruitment community 
outreach and the common enemies of drugs and gangs 
ola mae toler a watts resident since 1947 said watts has 
improved to the point a riot could not happen today 
i dont think people are thinking of that anymore she said 
theres a lot of people who want progress i know i do but i 
have never thought that watts was the worst place to live 
others say many of the reforms recommended in the mccone report 
never materialized got lost in the shuffle or were scaled down 
the lockheed aeronautics plant near the wattswillowbrook border 
built in response to the riots was closed in 1988 putting 
thousands of people out of work 
the martin luther king jrdrew medical center built south of 
watts to provide more accessible health care has been battered by 
allegations of administrative negligence and inadequate services 
the schools have a serious dropout problem the failure rate was 
35 percent at ds jordan high school in watts in the 198889 
school year and nearly 36 percent at locke high school just west 
of watts according to the los angeles unified school district 
estimates of unemployment run as high as 40 percent the county 
department of public social services says more than half of watts 
residents receive some sort of public assistance most of them 
children 
crime is rampant in watts and surrounding communities with 
homicides about one every four days in the police departments 
southeast division about a third of which is watts ninetyfour 
murders were committed in the division last year in the first half 
of this year 49 homicides were reported 
the ground gained in 65 for the most part has been lost 
said tommy jacquette a watts resident and head of the watts summer 
festival a local arts celebration health programs and human 
services programs have been cut out by local government 
organizations designed for selfhelp are gone then theres the 
onslaught of drugs and gang activities 
ucla professor james johnson director of the ucla center for 
the study of urban poverty describes watts as a community at war 
with itself with watts residents killing watts residents 
i personally dont think well have another watts rebellion of 
65 he said i think today it takes place on a daily basis 
</TEXT>
