<TEXT>
the woman was probably in her 20s but 
she had the look of those who have lost all hope at first glance 
she appeared at least 50 years old 
she sat in the tropical rain on the curb of sekou toure avenue 
with a daysold baby cradled in her lap the baby was crying in the 
darkness no one else was to be seen 
it was after curfew and she risked being shot by president 
samuel does soldiers 
passersby stopped to offer her dollars and to advise her to get 
her baby out of harms way she refused the money i want food 
she said i cant buy food with that 
she was told if she walked into territory held by rebel chief 
prince johnson she might get some red cross rice there had been a 
distribution of rice that morning in the part of monrovia 
the woman shook her head i couldnt make it she said 
im too weak to carry the baby 
it was a statement of fact not a cry for help 
liberias civil war trudges on in its heartless manner civilian 
lives matter little in the immediate battle for a street crossing 
or a gas station and reports from rebelheld territory indicate 
people there face the same dangers 
in the morning the woman had gone 
was she taken in by people living nearby or killed by the 
troops or had she just wandered down the deserted rubblestrewn 
street in search of what 
even news of an impending intervention by a force of troops from 
several west african nations couldnt lift the gloom 
i dont believe anyone can help us in the mess weve made of 
our country said elwyn jackson a gas station attendant until 
the war closed his station and government troops killed his boss 
monrovia has no first aid stations no facilities for the poor 
no one to whom to turn for help not even ambulances or fire 
brigades are functioning 
fires started in the fighting blazed out of control sometimes 
all night when the rain comes every day or so the flames go out 
by themselves in a sizzle of hell 
stray dogs abandoned lost wander through the streets their 
bones show through their backs and they have the strange slow 
movements of those too starved to care 
the rotting bloated corpses of the human victims are seen 
everywhere in strange postures in gutters on sidewalks along the 
beach or in the uncut weeds on empty plots of land 
theres no one to remove the bodies and no one is worrying 
about dying later from some disease spread by the corpses 
feet hands and faces of the corpses are often missing the 
bodies are being attacked under cover of darkness by rats to the 
stray dogs 
acnid farnat is a diminutative lebanese who used to run the 
arabic school on the seafront he still lives there but his 
students have long since gone 
he came to the nearby british embassy pleading for special help 
the odor from a human body that had washed up in front of his house 
was making his family sick he wanted help to move the body 
neither the british nor anyone else was willing to assist him 
the body remained where it was until it disappeared a few days 
later in the waves 
the downtown streets are empty cars without wheels or with 
their windows shot out are parked everywhere long past anyones 
capacity to get them moving again 
the steel shutters of supermarkets most of them owned by 
lebanese or indians who have long gone have been blown apart by 
rifle bullets their contents looted 
the crackling of machinegun fire whipping across the long 
straight streets has become part of daily life 
every morning the remaining downtown inhabitants slink out of 
their homes in search for food and water long lines of civilians 
can be seen making their way across the old bridge over the 
mezurado river toward a haphazard rice distribution set up by 
johnson 
on benson street there is a solitary figure in a red tshirt 
crouched on the sidewalk eating garbage 
he ignores the roadblock set up by johnsons freedom 
fighters across the street and they ignore him 
hes crazy said the sergeant in charge 
even if everyone in this town gets killed hell still be 
there 
</TEXT>
