<TEXT>
iraqis rushed to stock up on rice sugar 
cooking oil and other foodstuffs after economic sanctions were 
announced fearing shortages in a country that imports 2 billion 
worth of food a year 
after iraq invaded kuwait attention was focused on the world 
embargo on iraqs oil exports the food cutoff could impose even 
greater suffering on iraq 
because the world embargo applies to kuwait too the residents 
of the iraqiannexed emirate are likely to feel the food pinch just 
as much kuwait imports effectively all of its food 
foreigners who fled kuwait after the invasion reported immediate 
shortages as residents rushed to supermarkets and prepared for 
siegelike conditions 
londons financial times on thursday quoted a source inside 
kuwait whom it did not identify as saying in notes shipped to the 
newspaper tuesday morning some residents queuing at banks and 
food shops but no sign of them opening 
iraq imports about 70 percent of its food according to omar 
kader a middle east expert and board member of the arabamerican 
affairs council food accounts for a quarter of all iraqi imports 
and onethird of the food brought in comes from the united states 
it consists mainly of wheat corn rice barley sugar poultry and 
eggs at subsidized prices 
washington has also provided agricultural credits to the arab 
country 
even before the invasion the senate voted july 27 to halt 1 
billion in agricultural credit guarantees citing in part iraqs 
recent threat to use chemical weapons against israel 
that measure required presidential approval but became moot 
after the postinvasion sanctions cut off all credit 
omar kader a middle east expert and board member of the 
arabamerican affairs council said on good morning america 
that a food cutoff would have almost immediate impact 
the iraqi people are accustomed to shortages 
during the 198088 war with iran many foodstuffs were rationed 
including rice sugar and cooking oil people stood in lines 
stretching around city blocks to purchase small quantities at 
government stores 
local turkish and iraqi officials have been trying to figure out 
what to do about thousands of trucks blocked on both sides of the 
border since turkey decided to cut off trade with iraq 
turkey is both a supplier of food to iraq and a crucial overland 
route for imports from europe and other points 
a major route for iraqi food imports during the iraniraq war 
was the truck route from the port of aqaba in jordan a country 
where feelings in support of iraq run strong in some quarters 
but businessmen in jordan said ships carrying food or other 
products have not unloaded at aqaba since the un security council 
voted monday for global sanctions against iraq 
another possible route for food imports the long iraniraq 
border has been shut to trade since the 1980 outbreak of the 
iraniraq war it is now patrolled by un ceasefire monitors 
with no trade allowed across it 
marking an exception to the world blockade sri lanka said it 
would continue selling tea a major staple in every arab country 
to iraq despite the embargo 
we are a poor country and must continue to pick and sell our 
tea said deputy defense minister ranjaan wijeratne sanctions 
can be imposed by rich countries we cannot afford to stop selling 
our products 
iraq is sri lankas secondlargest customer after egypt having 
bought 24 percent of last years tea exports 
</TEXT>
