<DOCNO> AP900810-0010 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a federal judge thursday denied an environmental 
groups request to immediately halt the shipment of us chemical 
weapons from west germany to a pacific island pending a hearing 
later this month 
greenpeace usa had asked us district judge david ezra to grant 
a temporary restraining order preventing the army from moving the 
weapons from a storage site at clausen west germany to johnston 
atoll 800 miles southwest of honolulu 
ezra denied the request but scheduled a hearing on greenpeaces 
plea for a preliminary injunction for aug 20 
the decision was a partial victory for the bush administration 
which has pledged to remove the weapons from west germany by the 
end of the year government attorneys had said any halt in the 
shipment could delay the operation until 1991 
events unfolding in the middle east have painted up with 
precision and clarity the importance to the national security of 
the united states that commitments made by and between 
representatives of nations be honored ezras 21page ruling said 
greenpeace filed a lawsuit last week naming defense secretary 
dick cheney and michael p stone secretary of the army as 
defendants the organization said the munitions and plans to 
incinerate them pose a threat to the environment and people of the 
pacific 
government attorneys said johnston atoll is the safest location 
for the weapons they said every precaution has been taken to 
ensure the safety of the shipment 
ezra ruled that failing to immediately halt the shipment would 
not cause irreversible harm to the plaintiffs goal of keeping the 
army from transporting the munitions to johnston atoll since the 
weapons are not scheduled to leave west germany until next month 
the weapons are to be loaded onto trucks then transferred to 
rail cars bound for the north sea two us navy ships are to take 
the weapons to johnston atoll by an undisclosed route sometime 
after sept 1 
about 30 percent of the 100000 rounds of nerve gas shells 
already have been removed from the clausen facility or packed into 
shipping containers 
greenpeace attorney skip spaulding said he was confident the 
aug 20 hearing would allow him to prove the army has violated us 
environmental laws 
spaulding contended the army violated the national environmental 
policy act by not filing an environmental impact statement covering 
the movement of the weapons within west germany 
the army said it prepared an environmental impact statement on 
the ocean portion of the weapons journey to johnston however the 
report is classified and ezra has not seen it 
the army has yet to obtain approval to incinerate the weapons at 
the new johnston atoll chemical agent disposal system the facility 
is still being tested 
ezra said nothing leads him to believe us environmental laws 
apply in west germany when the removal of the munitions is being 
assisted by that nation however he said the laws do apply to the 
proposed incineration of the weapons at johnston atoll 
president bush has assured the west german government the 
weapons will be removed by the end of the year 
congress has required that all us chemical weapons be 
destroyed by 1997 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

