<TEXT>
the justice departments challenge to 
georgias majority vote election runoff system ultimately could aid 
republican candidates in the south and southwest not blacks a 
political observer says 
the department sued thursday contending that georgias election 
runoff system has had a chilling effect on black political 
participation 
ten states in the south and southwest have laws requiring a 
runoff election if no candidate receives a majority of the votes in 
a general election 
the republican party can be made overnight in the south if 
that runoff law is eliminated said claiborne darden an 
atlantabased pollster that would do more for the republican 
party than republicans could do for themselves in 125 years 
without runoff elections darden said blacks would win more 
democratic primaries but they would lose general elections to gop 
candidates backed by white voters who previously supported white 
democratic candidates he said 
john r dunne assistant attorney general for civil rights said 
more than 35 black candidates in over 20 counties in georgia have 
finished first in multicandidate primary elections in recent 
years only to lose in runoffs against a single white candidate 
he said the law amounts to an electoral steroid for white 
candidates because it gives them an extraordinary power over 
black candidates in states with racially polarized voting 
the suit filed in us district court in atlanta contends that 
the 1964 georgia law requiring candidates to receive a majority of 
the vote to win an election deprives black voters of an equal 
opportunity to elect candidates of their choice 
the suit marks the first time the justice department has used 
the 1965 voting rights act to challenge a states majority vote 
runoff system a position jesse jackson first advocated during his 
1984 presidential campaign 
jackson tried unsuccessfully that year to persuade the 
democratic party to take a stand against majority vote runoff 
elections in its presidential platform democratic presidential 
nominee walter mondale opposed the effort 
jacksons georgia coordinator in 1984 state rep tyrone brooks 
of atlanta renewed the effort earlier this year when he filed suit 
in federal court asking that georgias runoff system be invalidated 
a federal judge refused to rule on the issue before this 
summers georgia elections former atlanta mayor andrew young who 
was seeking to become georgias first black governor opposed the 
lawsuit 
young finished second in the democratic primary and then was 
swamped by lt gov zell miller in tuesdays runoff election 
the runoff law however has made the political careers of other 
georgia leaders sen sam nunn gov joe frank harris and rep 
john lewis all georgia democrats were elected for the first time 
after finishing second in democratic primaries and then winning the 
runoff 
i think the runoff is enormously important and i think 
majority rule is important nunn said thursday and i believe 
that if you deprive the people of the right to make that decision 
by majority votes youve greatly damaged the election process 
asked if he believed the suit was an effort by republicans to 
weaken the democratic party in the south nunn said i wouldnt 
want to make that charge but i certainly disagree with the justice 
department getting involved in this 
dunne said the department has no immediate plans to challenge 
the election systems in alabama arizona arkansas florida 
louisiana oklahoma mississippi south carolina and texas the 
only other states with laws requiring a majority vote to be 
nominated or elected to office 
but he said those state runoff laws because of their similarity 
to the georgia law likely would be overturned should the 
department prevail in the georgia case 
dunne said the departments lawsuit challenges only elections 
where the majority vote requirement has been used to dilute the 
voting strength of minorities that would include most statewide 
elections he said and many local elections where blacks are a 
large bloc of the voting population but have been unable to elect 
black candidates 
dunne said about 24 percent of georgias voting age population 
is black but less than 10 percent of the elected offices in the 
state are held by blacks and most of those are at the local level 
</TEXT>
