<TEXT>
the vital interest america sees in saudi 
arabia is no mystery its the oil the desert kingdom sits on a 
sea of crude whose flow is crucial for running the engines of the 
modern global economy 
saudi arabia is the worlds biggest oil exporter and its 255 
billion barrels of proven reserves give it 25 percent of the 
worlds total 
the sovereign independence of saudi arabia is of vital 
interest to the united states president bush said in dispatching 
american troops to face off with menacing iraq 
experts agree that if saudi oil fell to conquest destruction or 
intimidation the consequences would be devastating 
the word unthinkable is correct said john lichtblau 
chairman of the petroleum industry research foundation if saudi 
arabia were out 7 millionbarrels a day would be lost you couldnt 
close the gap with prices youd have to have worldwide rationing 
and shortages 
it gets worse any set of events that blocks saudi oil would 
presumably cut supplies from other persian gulf oil exporters as 
well certainly abu dhabi and maybe iran who knows what would 
happen next 
it would be a major international conflict lichtblau said 
oil would no longer be the only consideration 
but the oil shortage would certainly be a major consideration 
if only because petroleum is so essential to the modern way of life 
gasoline of course powers nearly all the 180 million cars 
trucks and buses on americas roads many people use oil or 
liquefied petroleum gas to heat their homes and power companies 
consume 730000 barrels a day generating electricity 
besides petroleum products and derivatives are used in items as 
diverse as detergents plastics fertilizers drugs paint 
cosmetics and clothing 
so far this year saudi arabia has exported more than 12 
million barrels of oil a day to the united states covering about 
75 percent of the nations consumption a barrel contains 42 
gallons 
the saudis have been pumping 53 million barrels a day recently 
nearly 10 percent of what is consumed worldwide excluding the 
soviet union and eastern europe which is how the figures are still 
compiled 
many people believe the saudis now will boost output to more 
than 7 million barrels replacing nearly half of the iraqi oil 
being blocked by a worldwide embargo 
if saudi arabia increases production that puts them in a more 
overt confrontation with iraq said james e akins a former us 
ambassador to saudi arabia wed have to assume there would be an 
attempt by iraq to sabotage saudi oil production 
the oil fields of saudi arabia as it happens are concentrated 
in the east near the borders with kuwait and iraq making them all 
the more vulnerable to attack even if american and other forces 
are able to keep iraq from gobbling up the saudis as it did tiny 
kuwait it would be hard to prevent any damage 
its a huge complex its very difficult to protect every 
checkpoint akins said 
increased production from countries outside the region such as 
mexico and venezuela will not be enough to replace the missing 
iraqi oil let alone cover for a disaster in saudi arabia 
the united states has about 600 million barrels of crude oil in 
its strategic petroleum reserve which should be able to deliver up 
to 35 million barrels a day to refineries if bush orders it 
tapped west germany japan and other industrial powers have 
similar emergency oil reserves 
akins joined other critics in urging bush to release oil 
immediately from the strategic reserve to head off panicky price 
increases and lines at gasoline stations 
he also said it was time to put a gas rationing system in place 
to be ready if drastic shortages and zooming prices make it 
necessary 
price rationing would be catastrophic physical rationing need 
not be catastrophic akins said 
