<TEXT>
wholesale prices declined 01 percent in july 
the government said friday in a report showing inflation was in 
check before iraqs invasion of kuwait last week sent oil costs 
spiraling 
the seasonally adjusted decline capped a sixmonth stretch of 
virtually no change in the labor departments producer price index 
for finished goods the index had risen a modest 02 percent in 
june 
for the first seven months of the year wholesale prices 
advanced at an annual rate of 3 percent down sharply from the 48 
percent increase for all of last year 
obviously this number is history said economist donald 
ratajczak of georgia state university but what it shows is that 
heading into the oil shock inflation was tame 
financial markets shrugged off the good news stock prices fell 
after iraqi president saddam hussein called for arab unity to 
condemn us forces in saudi arabia and to overthrow the saudi 
royal family 
the effect on world oil markets of iraqs action last week means 
the july report is the end of the inflation respite analysts said 
the numbers almost appear like the calm beach scene before the 
shark in jaws arrives said ron schreibman vice president of 
the national association of wholesalerdistributors 
crude oil prices which averaged around 20 a barrel in july 
have pushed past 25 since the invasion and gasoline prices are 
reported up as much as 16 cents a gallon at many service stations 
ratajczak predicted that overall wholesale prices could shoot up 
as much as 16 percent in august that would be the biggest 
increase since a 19 percent jump in january when a severe cold 
snap froze vegetable crops and dried up fuel oil supplies 
in july energy prices fell 05 percent the sixth consecutive 
decline food costs were unchanged and prices excluding the 
volatile food and energy sectors considered a better indicator of 
underlying inflationary pressures fell 01 percent the first 
drop in a year 
the prospect of accelerating inflation at the same time the 
economy seems on the verge of recession presents a dilemma for the 
federal reserve the central bank has been fighting inflation by 
cooling the economy with relatively high interest rates 
but last month the fed nudged shortterm rates lower in response 
to signs that businesses were having trouble obtaining loans 
economist david jones of aubrey g lanston amp co a government 
securities dealer in new york said monetary policy makers will 
look beyond the oil shock which they cannot influence and pay 
close attention to recent signs of accumulating economic weakness 
those include a leap in the civilian unemployment rate from 52 
percent in june to 55 percent in july the highest in two years 
the handwriting is on the wall for the fed its going to have 
to ease the question is whether its going to ease right away or 
whether its going to wait until its aug 21 meeting he said 
the labor department offered these details of july prices 
gasoline fell 53 percent while natural gas rose 66 percent 
and fuel oil was up 04 percent 
fresh fruit prices jumped 14 percent but egg prices declined 
183 percent costs were up for rice pasta chicken fish and soft 
drinks prices fell for vegetables baked goods beef pork and 
shortening and cooking oil 
clothing prices were mixed with a 02 percent rise for girls 
childrens and infants apparel a 01 percent drop in mens and 
boys clothing and no change in womens clothing 
passenger car prices dropped 05 percent household glassware 
fell 51 percent but silverware rose 41 percent 
tobacco prices fell 29 percent but they had been rising 
steadily before and were still 133 percent higher than a year ago 
the various changes put the producer price index for all 
finished goods at 1180 in july that means a hypothetical 
selection of goods that cost 100 in 1982 cost 118 last month up 
from 11410 a year earlier 
in earlier stages of the production process prices were 
unchanged for intermediate goods and rose 06 percent for crude 
goods an example of the three processing stages would be clothing 
for finished goods cloth for intermediate and cotton for crude 
</TEXT>
