the military hospital ship usns comfort will 
sail saturday from baltimore on the first leg of a trip to support 
troops in the middle east the navy said friday 
the ship will be staffed with nearly 1200 doctors and other 
personnel from the national naval medical center in bethesda md 
all elective surgery at the 350bed military hospital was suspended 
friday in anticipation of the ships deployment 
the ship will head to norfolk va on saturday to pick up 
supplies said margaret holtz a spokeswoman for the military 
sealift command which controls the ship in domestic ports 
from there holtz said it will sail in support of operation 
desert shield the militarys name for the deployment of us 
troops to protect saudi arabia from attack by iraq 
spokesman hb auld said bethesda would be on a reduced 
status 
comfort is one of two floating hospitals operated by the navy 
the other the usns mercy is docked in oakland calif 
if either ship puts to sea in response to the american buildup 
of forces on the arabian peninsula it will be the first time that 
navy hospital ship has been activated fully since the vietnam war 
the comfort commissioned as a hospital ship in 1986 is a 
converted san clemente class tanker it is 894 feet long 105 feet 
wide and is equipped with 1000 hospital beds 
medical facilities on board include surgical suites intensive 
care wards and equipment and general wards unlike most ships it 
has wide hospitalstyle stairways and hallways to accommodate easy 
transfer of patients 
for emergency medical care the ship has the best available of 
everything auld said 
it can do everything from treating a hangnail to major 
surgery he said 
the ship is normally staffed by 1000 medical and logistic 
workers these would include doctors of virtually every speciality 
dentists corpsmen and nurses the ship itself is run by 80 
civilian workers who man the vessel constantly even while it is in 
port 
comforts wide decks will accommodate helicopters making it 
possible to bring wounded or injured service directly to the vessel 
from a combat zone 
normally the comfort would provide immediate lifesaving care 
once an injury or wound is stabilized the patient is shifted to 
permanent hospitals on shore 
