<TEXT>
fisheries officials using small 
boats and a helicopter tried to keep dozens of stubborn pilot 
whales from returning to shore and certain death off cape 
breton friday 
several closeknit groups of about 20 whales called pods 
stayed about 1 miles off the west coast of cape breton island 
throughout the day after being coaxed back into the water thursday 
said tom kiely acting regional manager for the federal fisheries 
department 
at least two whales died thursday as fisheries officials 
tourists and residents tried to rescue dozens of whales on the 
beach near cheticamp 
rescuers doubted that the approximately 60 who lived could 
survive being stranded again because of cuts and scratches they 
suffered while thrashing around in the shallow waters 
whale expert john lien a professor of animal behavior at 
memorial university in st johns newfoundland said the whales 
may have beached themselves because they were about to die anyway 
he said it is normal for pilot whales common in the waters of 
atlantic canada to be involved in between three and five 
strandings each year 
the reasons remain unknown some believe beachings occur when a 
pod follows a sick leader ashore or when subterranean geological 
faults hamper their navigation 
pilot whales a toothed species also called blackfish are among 
the smaller members of the whale family growing up to 20 feet in 
length and weighing up to three tons 
</TEXT>
