looting broke out in dozens of poor 
neighborhoods friday in an angry reaction to president alberto 
fujimoris harsh austerity program 
in the villa el salvador shantytown soldiers fired over the 
heads of a stonethrowing mob of 2000 that gathered in front of 
the local market demanding that it open 
police used tear gas and clubs to control about 3000 peruvians 
in limas atevitarte section the people had been waiting for up 
to two days for subsidized sugar but the supply ran out friday 
looting began immediately after the government announced an 
extreme economic austerity program wednesday night gasoline prices 
jumped from seven cents to more than 2 the cost of many basic 
foods tripled or quadrupled 
telephone water and electricity rates will rise as will taxes 
on the rich lower import duties and a freefloating dollar are in 
store 
the program aims to slash perus 3000 percent annual inflation 
rate by eliminating subsidies the subsidies are largely 
responsible for perus huge fiscal deficit which in turn spurs the 
government to print money to cover costs 
fujimoris plan also is intended to reactivate an economy in 
which four of five people lack steady work 
at first the measures at first brought lima to a near halt 
most stores were closed thursday and buses did not run 
life in downtown lima and in the capitals wealthier 
neighborhoods was largely back to normal friday with stores open 
and some public transportation available restaurants were largely 
empty 
but the poor areas have been hard hit most people there buy 
food day to day few had money enough to buy the basics friday 
most markets were closed for fear of looting venders often 
charged double the prices in supermarkets in wealthier 
neighborhoods 
people blamed the government 
theyre strangling us albina urcaya said as she stood for 
the third day in the sugar line in atevitarte they pull us out 
of one crisis just to throw us into a much deeper hole 
julia pomachagua stood nearby caressing the head of her 
5yearold son he hasnt eaten breakfast or lunch 
