<DOCNO> AP900810-0167 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the united states has achieved only limited 
success with coercive economic sanctions like those being used 
against iraq in part because of the difficulty in rallying the 
rest of the world behind them 
but saddam husseins invasion of kuwait may have changed the 
nature of the game 
in the week since iraqi tanks lumbered across the kuwaiti 
border the oildependent world with a rarely seen unanimity has 
cut off iraqi oil shipments barred all trade with iraq and frozen 
billions of dollars of kuwaiti assets to shield them from iraqi 
looting 
at the same time us forces are being deployed to the middle 
east to guard against an iraqi invasion of saudi arabia 
i would think that if this international lesson is taught 
well saddam hussein would act differently in the future 
president bush told a news conference last week a line has 
been drawn in the sand were getting strong support from around 
the world for what weve done 
the economic offensive against iraq has long and tangled roots 
in 432 bc the athenian leader pericles declared economic war 
against megara a rival greek city state history does not record 
the results 
but the results were clear in 1935 after the league of nations 
imposed sanctions against benito mussolinis italy for its invasion 
of abyssinia now ethiopia 
there was no deterrent effect although the action was seen by 
some as a public relations boon for participating countries 
british political leader lloyd george said cynically that the 
sanctions came too late to save abyssinia but theyre just in 
the nick of time to save the british government 
in the early 1980s a grain embargo imposed by president carter 
failed to persuade the soviet union to withdraw from afghanistan 
moscow found the grain it needed elsewhere 
american farmers complained they had been forced to suffer 
needlessly critics said the united states had aimed at the soviet 
bear and shot itself in the foot a phrase used repeatedly 
since then by congressional opponents of other attempts to impose 
sanctions 
in a 1985 study published by the institute for international 
economics gary clyde and jeffrey schott said economic sanctions 
had been used successfully only 39 times since 1914 in the 
remaining 69 cases they said the sanctions had little effect 
american attempts to use the economic weapon have most often 
failed because other countries could not be persuaded to follow the 
us lead 
john spanier professor of political science at the university 
of florida says sanctions work best when there is widespread 
agreement by many nations about the wisdom or necessity of 
employing them 
individual national sanctions are rarely effective he said 
in his book games nations play 
sanctions will inflict only temporary pain if alternative 
sources of supplies and export markets are available spanier 
said 
some examples of washingtons experience with sanctions 
in 1988 us sanctions wrecked the fragile panamanian economy 
but did not dislodge the countrys ruler gen manuel antonio 
noriega it took a us invasion to do that 
the longstanding us embargo of fidel castros cuba has done 
little to erode his hold on the country but has caused considerable 
economic difficulty 
bushs economic sanctions against china after the 1989 massacre 
in tiananmen square in beijing resulted in only token moderation in 
that nations policies some of those sanctions have been eased 
president carters decision to stop us purchases of iranian 
oil after the 1979 seizure of the us embassy in tehran gave an 
impression the administration was acting firmly in the hostage 
crisis but it was largely symbolic since the united states 
purchased little iranian oil 
on the other hand the sanctions imposed by the united states 
and other nations against south africas white minority government 
may have significantly slowed that nations rate of economic growth 
and been a potent psychological factor in persuading white leaders 
to deal with the black majority 
aside from iraq us economic sanctions still are in effect 
against south africa libya cuba vietnam north korea and 
cambodia 
before the kuwaiti invasion the bush administration had 
objected to proposals for sanctions against iraq 
john kelly assistant secretary of state for middle eastern 
affairs told the senate foreign relations committee on june 15 
that based on past experience we do not believe that legislating 
unilateral trade and economic sanctions would help us to achieve 
us goals with iraq 
he said then that there was no prospect then that other 
nations would follow the us lead 
the situation changed drastically after saddams troops headed 
into kuwait 
the united states was joined by the soviet union in a joint 
condemnation of iraq moscow cut off the flow of weapons to its 
erstwhile middle east ally iraqs other major arms suppliers 
including china said they would do the same 
the 12nation european economic community followed the united 
states in imposing stiff economic sanctions so did japan 
the united nations security council voted comprehensive and 
mandatory trade and business sanctions and directed saudi arabia 
and turkey to cut off the flow of iraqi oil through pipelines which 
cross their national territory 
british prime minister margaret thatcher conceded a naval 
blockade might be necessary to stop the export of iraqi oil by 
ship and bush dispatched air naval and ground forces to shield 
saudi arabia from possible iraqi attack 
while some questioned the longterm will of the united states 
and its allies to accept the sanctionrelated rise in oil prices 
others were optimistic that the sanctions would work 
sen richard lugar rind a former chairman of the senate 
foreign relations committee said iraqs wealth comes only from 
oil and it is a food dependent country that leaves it in a state 
of comparative weakness sanctions on food and oil will cause grave 
damage to the economy of iraq 
during the reagan administration after iraq had been accused of 
using poison gas against its kurdish minority the senate voted 
three times and the house twice to impose sanctions against iraq 
but the administration successfully squelched them on grounds 
that they would hurt us agricultural exports and hinder rather 
than enhance efforts to encourage hussein to show restraint 
senate foreign relations committee chairman claiborne pell 
dri said the failure to send hussein a strong message against 
the use of poison gas may have encouraged him on the path that 
eventually led his tanks across the kuwaiti border 
</TEXT>
