<TEXT>
this isnt the first time americans have been 
forced to pay more for gas while us oil companies profited from 
turmoil in the middle east 
think back 17 years to the arab oil embargo of 1973 to lines 
at gas stations and rules restricting fillups to odd or even days 
the circumstances were different but the scenario was the same 
the nozzle of the gas pump was held to uncle sams head like a gun 
despite the jolt of that fivemonth embargo and a replay in 1979 
during the iranian revolution the united states is more dependent 
than ever on foreign countries for its oil habit 
this country went back to sleep on energy about 1980 now 
were in a defensive position and we dont have a game plan said 
david freeman a california utility executive and an energy adviser 
to presidents johnson and nixon 
we were led to believe by our leaders in the 1980s we could 
have a party we could go back to gas guzzling and we could 
continue the joyride freeman said to continue the joyride on 
arab oil is a risky proposition 
the 1973 action was a producer embargo the organization of 
petroleum exporting countries shut off the tap to the united states 
for its support of israel in the 1973 war with egypt 
whats going on today is a consumer embargo the united states 
wont take any oil from iraq because of its aug 2 absorption of 
kuwait so americans must either make up the difference somewhere 
else or make sacrifices 
although there is no shortage of oil in the united states or the 
world prices rose 18 cents a gallon at the pump by friday seven 
airlines also raised ticket prices to offset higher fuel costs 
reaction was as wrathful as it was in 1973 when most americans 
blamed the oil companies and the government for their plight and 
not the arabs according to the national opinion research center in 
chicago 
oil companies back then pocketed record profits while gasoline 
escalated from 39 cents a gallon to 53 cents before the embargo 
ended march 18 1974 
a more cynical view lays the fault for this countrys present 
difficulties to the economic greed of the oil industry the 
american association for the advancement of science said in a study 
at the time 
compare that to current charges of war profiteering 
the big oil companies have gone on a feeding frenzy this 
isnt panic this is greed said sen richard bryan dnev 
chairman of the senate consumer subcommittee 
theyre ripping us off said new york gov mario cuomo 
