japans trade surplus shrank 103 percent in july 
from a year earlier largely due to increased imports the finance 
ministry said friday 
the ministry said the countrys trade surplus declined to 538 
billion in july from 599 billion a year earlier on a customs 
clearance basis 
imports rose 60 percent to 1850 billion from a year earlier 
while exports rose 18 percent to 2388 billion the ministry said 
the drop in the surplus marks a return to a recent declining 
trend in japans trade gap which had been steadily falling since 
june 1989 until june 1990 when it jumped 276 percent 
ministry officials said a record increase in the imports of 
finished products including an 82 percent increase in aircraft and 
440 percent increase in imports of works of art contributed to the 
rise in imports 
the officials noted concern about economic sanctions and oil 
embargoes against iraq and kuwait decided earlier in the week 
on a regional basis japans trade surplus with the united 
states narrowed 206 percent to 307 billion from a year earlier 
its surplus with the european community shrank 298 percent to 
115 billion while its surplus with asia rose 42 percent to 248 
billion the ministry said 
japan calculates its trade surplus on a customsclearance basis 
which includes freight and insurance costs in imports but not in 
exports 
