<DOCNO> AP900810-0190 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when the indian government ended its 
37year monopoly on airlines in april visions of bellydancing 
hostesses undulated through deepak anands head 
anand one of indias new breed of capitalists has yet to 
realize his dream of sashaying stewardesses 
but he has a private airline flying in india for the first time 
since the country nationalized eight carriers in 1953 
ub air took to the skies on june 1 led by anand who is 
corporate planner for the ub group indias biggest beer brewery 
and one of the countrys largest companies 
on time every time is ub airs slogan its nickname is 
beer air in reference to the companys main product and 
anand said the airline would soon relaunch canned beer in india by 
offering ubs black label and kingfisher brews on board a first in 
india 
ub air is targeting business travelers with fares about 30 
percent higher than indian airlines anand says he is committed to 
getting people where they want to go in time for their business 
meetings 
i also wanted belly dancers anand said but i got shot 
down company officials thought dancing on board would be too 
disruptive he said 
many seem to be taking ub air seriously 
it began by flying the 180 miles from bangalore a southern city 
of hightech industries and 4 million people to mangalore a beach 
resort on the west coast since june it has added a route from 
bangalore to the eastern city of madras a round trip to hyderabad 
in central india and the capital new delhi are also planned 
as of late july the company had flown about 60 flights all of 
them have been on time a highly unusual occurrence in india the 
land of the endless wait 
when 18000 indian airlines employees went on strike july 12 
ub air responded with two special flights to madras 
it was fun to stick it to them anand said it was our 
small way of saying wake up india 
the young airline operates with a single plane a 15seater 
donnier 228100 which flies six round trips a week between 
bangalore madras and mangalore 
next month ub air pans to purchase a 19seater donnier 228201 
from druk air bhutans staterun airline it is also trying to 
lease a 77seater bae146 jet from druk 
the appearance of a private airline in indias skies highlights 
attempts made by recent governments to liberalize this vast 
nations rigid economy 
since independence from britain in 1947 india has sheltered 
itself from the world economic system erecting huge tariffs on 
items from bicycles to automobiles to soft drinks most major 
industries such as power steel transportation and communication 
were state run 
when rajiv gandhi became prime minister in 1984 he moved to 
increase indias competition with the outside world lowering some 
tariffs and pushing trade 
gandhis loss in the 1989 election to vp singh didnt stop 
this process in may the government announced a new industrial 
policy approving foreign investment as long as the foreign partner 
holds less than 40 percent equity 
the government also opened up indias staterun power industry 
to private investors and the ministry of defense published a list 
of items which could be produced domestically by private industry 
in april the government announced its open skies policy 
permitting private airlines to fly 
many thought the announcement was overdue in indias air 
industry the gap between supply and demand has been acute 
of indias three stateowned airlines air india indian 
airlines and vayudoot only air india is considered passable and 
its flights are mainly overseas one airline analyst in hong kong 
called indian airlines the worst way to travel east of iran 
vayudoot lost an estimated 25 million last year 
even with liberalization the government is not allowing fair 
competition in the skies private airlines are prohibited from 
advertising schedules and are banned from using indias foreign 
exchange to buy airplanes 
as such indias fledgling airlines will have to rely on wary 
foreign banks or rich nonresident indians interested in investing 
in their homeland for funds to buy planes ub air is currently 
negotiating with west germanys deutschebank for a loan said 
devapriya guha a senior manager in corporate planning 
still anand and other entrepreneurs remain undaunted 
competition is a process that india cannot avoid he said 
its the only way to improve service and enter the modern world 
</TEXT>
