<TEXT>
north carolinas attorney general filed a 
lawsuit friday against exxon corp charging the oil company with 
deceptive trade practices since the iraqi invasion of kuwait last 
week 
attorney general lacy thornburg charged that exxon is quoting 
wholesale prices which it fails to honor and is imposing 
retroactive wholesale price increases superior court judge robert 
farmer signed an injunction to halt the practice 
a spokesman for exxon said officials were unaware of the lawsuit 
and had no immediate comment 
north carolinas action follows the aug 2 invasion of kuwait 
which set off a spiral of higher gasoline prices across the united 
states 
the lawsuit is based on an investigation by the attorney 
generals office which uncovered documents showing that exxon had 
raised its wholesale prices by as much as 6 cents a gallon after 
having already contracted and sold the gas at the lower price 
thornburg said records indicate that in some cases distributors 
had picked up loads and already made deliveries to service stations 
before being informed of the price hikes 
documents show that some oil and gas distributors have suffered 
significant losses by relying on exxons alleged misrepresentation 
of price thornburg said 
according to the lawsuit because the exxon distributors dont 
know whether exxon will impose retroactive price increases on gas 
which they have already purchased the distributors must build a 
cushion into their resale prices 
ultimately the public pays the price thornburg said 
when exxon or any other company unfairly raises its prices to the 
distributors it sets off a chain reaction of price increases which 
hit the consumer in the pocketbook 
</TEXT>
