a us district court judge friday set a aside a 
159 million jury verdict against gte products corp calling for 
a new trial in a case filed by an inventor who claimed the company 
stole his idea 
the jury in june had awarded the money to george panagiotou a 
former rock band manager who had charged gte appropriated trade 
secrets for his cool lamp which is used in movie studios 
gte had maintained that panagiotou failed to show that any trade 
secrets existed or a contract had been breached 
judge john j mcnaught set aside the verdict but panagiotous 
attorney sydelle pittas said an appeal is likely 
it was a big award but we feel that the grounds on which it 
was set aside are not valid and are confident of winning an appeal 
of the judges decision she said 
a spokesman for gte said the company is pleased with the judges 
decision gte welcomes the retrial and the opportunity to 
completely vindicate itself the company said in a prepared 
statement 
panagiotous lawyers had argued that he started developing the 
cool light when he realized how uncomfortable performers were under 
the heat of movie studio lamps in the 1970s 
his cool lights were used in the production of numerous popular 
television shows the trial originally filed in california in 
1984 brought such television stars as ed asner and michael landon 
to testify on panagiotous behalf 
panagiotou has since started a successful home video light 
company in los angeles 
