<TEXT>
the stock market tumbled and oil prices climbed friday as 
belligerent rhetoric by iraqi president saddam hussein unnerved 
investors and heightened fears of an oil shortage 
were still seeing an underlying tension swelling in that 
region said randall rothenberg a oil broker with dean witter 
reynolds inc in new york the situation has not been averted 
the stock market closed the week with its worst performance 
since monday as virtually all sectors except gold and oil were 
battered by tensions in the middle east 
the dow jones average of 30 bluechip industrial stocks fell 
4233 points to 271658 extending its weekly drop to 9307 points 
analysts had expected some selling by investors reluctant to 
hold on to stocks in case of further developments over the weekend 
but saddam called for a holy war against western forces 
while arab nations agreed to dispatch troops to saudi arabia where 
us forces are positioned in what president bush called a defense 
against iraqi invasion 
bush raised tensions by warning iraq against sending out oil 
tankers to evade an economic embargo he also said saddam would be 
foolish to invade saudi arabia 
those events created jitters in the oil futures market on a 
belief they might lead to further disruptions of oil supplies from 
the middle east a critical source of world fuel a supply shortage 
would boost demand in turn pushing up prices 
on the new york mercantile exchange the september contract for 
us crude oil rose 56 cents to 2623 per 42gallon barrel crude 
oil has risen nealry 6 per barrel since the iraqi invasion aug 2 
among refined petroleum products traded on the merc the 
nearterm contract for home heating oil soared 284 cents to 7261 
cents per gallon the september contract for unleaded gasoline 
jumped 303 cents to 7945 cents per gallon 
in addition to saddams speech oil futures prices were helped 
by a statement by venezuela denying it planned to raise output to 
cover production by iraq and kuwait western nations have embargoed 
oil from the two nations 
meanwhile gasoline prices at the pump dropped for the first 
time since iraq invaded kuwait the automobile association of 
america said the average price of unleaded fuel nationwide was down 
03 cent friday to 125 a gallon 
on other financial markets gold for current delivery jumped 
1110 a troy ounce to close at 39690 on new yorks commodity 
exchange the dollar was lower against most major currencies 
despite the threat of escalating hostilities 
gold rose because it is viewed as a safe haven in times of 
distress and as a hedge against inflation likely to result from the 
sharp increase in oil prices 
